nation in the pre-modern world cannot adequately be captured using a linear, militarily framed conceptualization. The scope and varying perspectives on the spatial imagination analyzed in the volume's essays reveal a complex range of aspects that informs how space was designed and utilized. Due to the complexity and advanced scholarly level of the papers, the primary readership will be other scholars and advanced graduate students in history, history of science, geography, art history, religious studies, literature, and, broadly, sinology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh1 aHsu-Tang, H.M. Agnes, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeung, Vincent S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLycas, Alexis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorgan, Daniel Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPagenstecher Olberding, Garret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPagenstecher Olberding, Garret, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPing, Foong, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPowers, Martin J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRui Feng, Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb0 cEPUBz97831107499220 cprintz978311074965640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783110749823zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110749823zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110749823/original  